# Boolean Arithmetic and the ALU

Computers represent numbers in binary and perform arithmetic using logic gates. In this chapter, we build a family of adder chips culminating in the **Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU)** — the calculating brain of the CPU.

## Binary Numbers

In binary, each digit is a power of 2:

```
1101 = 1x8 + 1x4 + 0x2 + 1x1 = 13
```

For negative numbers, we use **two's complement**: -x = 2^n - x. Addition and subtraction share the same hardware.

## Half Adder

Adds two bits, producing sum and carry:

```hdl
CHIP HalfAdder {
    IN a, b;
    OUT sum, carry;
    PARTS:
    Xor(a=a, b=b, out=sum);
    And(a=a, b=b, out=carry);
}
```

## Full Adder

Adds three bits (two inputs plus carry-in):

```hdl
CHIP FullAdder {
    IN a, b, c;
    OUT sum, carry;
    PARTS:
    HalfAdder(a=a, b=b, sum=s1, carry=c1);
    HalfAdder(a=s1, b=c, sum=sum, carry=c2);
    Or(a=c1, b=c2, out=carry);
}
```

## The ALU

The Hack ALU is controlled by six control bits (zx, nx, zy, ny, f, no). It computes 18 different functions on two 16-bit inputs, including 0, 1, -1, x, y, !x, !y, -x, -y, x+1, y+1, x-1, y-1, x+y, x-y, y-x, x&y, and x|y.

The ALU also outputs **zr** (out=0) and **ng** (out<0) status bits.

