Crash Course Computer Science explains how Boolean logic gates combine to perform arithmetic.
:::

## Think Critically

:::evaluate{criteria="alu-design"}

### Why these control bits?

The ALU uses exactly six control bits. Could we have used fewer? What trade-offs exist between the number of control bits and the complexity of the ALU's internal logic?

### Criteria
- Analyzes the relationship between control bits and function space
- Considers hardware complexity vs. instruction width trade-off
- Recognizes that fewer control bits would require more internal logic
:::

## Project

:::project{environment="node" template="nand2tetris-project2"}

### Objective

Build the ALU and all supporting adder chips for the Hack computer.

### Requirements
1. Implement HalfAdder, FullAdder, Add16, Inc16
2. Implement the ALU (first without zr/ng, then with them)
3. Pass all supplied test scripts
4. Your ALU must compute all 18 documented functions correctly

### Hints
- Build the ALU in two stages: first the 16-bit output, then add zr/ng
- Use built-in versions of chips from Project 1 to keep simulation fast
- The ALU is purely combinational — no clock, no memory
:::
